Restaurant Finance Across America / October 2013 / Ruby Tuesday Chair Sells Stock, Resigns 



 
 Ruby Tuesday Chair Sells Stock, Resigns By Jonathan Maze

Published: 2013.10.28 10:14 AM





	File the following information under "Ominous Signs for Ruby Tuesday:"

	The chain's chairman, Matthew Drapkin, unloaded 1.45 million shares in Ruby Tuesday on Friday. On Sunday he resigned, and was replaced by the company's CEO, JJ Buettgen.

	Ruby Tuesday noted the change in a terse, three-sentence SEC filing this morning. It noted that the chairman change was effective "immediately."

	What's more, Drapkin barely profited from the sale. In 2011, Drapkin along with Steven Becker and their Dallas-based investment firm, Becker Drapkin Management, bought up 883,000 shares, paying $8.3 million. Drapkin amassed more shares as a director and then chairman, and sold most of those shares on Friday for $5.90 to $5.95 a share, or around $8.6 million.

	Drapkin had quickly taken a major role in the company after he and Becker paired with Carlson Capital in 2011 to form an activist investor group. Ruby Tuesday, under founder Sandy Beall, quickly gave the group two seats on its board rather than face a proxy fight. Carlson Capital and Becker Drapkin then split their group.

	Beall ultimately retired. Buettgen replaced him as CEO late last year, and Drapkin was elevated to the chairmanship.

	But results have been hard to come by this year amid a tough environment for casual dining concepts—an environment so tough that even a one-time bright spot like BJ's Restaurants has suffered sales declines. Ruby Tuesday's primary competitors, Chili's and Applebee's, have been marketing heavily and investing in their stores. Price competition has been intense. And Ruby Tuesday has shifted its product strategy from Beall's failed upscaling idea back to its lower-cost, burger-centric roots.

	The chain's struggles were punctuated by a same-store sales decline of 11.4 percent in its most recent quarter and predictions that comparable store sales will be down in the "high single digits" this year as the chain adjusts. 

	Remember: Ruby Tuesday had been flirting with bankruptcy before a surprisingly good quarter in 2009 led to a surge in its stock price that enabled the company to use a secondary offering to pay down some debt.

	Now, Ruby Tuesday is sinking again. And its chairman just sold stock and abandoned ship.


